Hey Lila,

Have you ever read The Checklist Manifesto (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/5qu6rgzg5kc7hw0nxmc6/owhkhqh4oq26g2av/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9DaGVja2xpc3QtTWFuaWZlc3RvLUhvdy1UaGluZ3MtUmlnaH=
QvZHAvMDMxMjQzMDAwMD8mbGlua0NvZGU9c2wxJnRhZz1lMDNmZDctMjAmbGlua0lkPTdiNzliN=
DVjOTQ1ODk5Yzc2NmNmYjM4MWQ2Nzc0MWM1Jmxhbmd1YWdlPWVuX1VTJnJlZl89YXNfbGlfc3Nf=
dGw=3D
)? It=E2=80=99s life-changing... and yet kind of silly.

I=E2=80=99ll save you 4 hours with this 2-word summary: use checklists! =F0=
=9F=A4=93

(OK, a lot goes into why they=E2=80=99re awesome and underrated =E2=80=93 i=
t=E2=80=99s
actually a good book)

Both Learn UI Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/5qu6rgzg5kc7hw0nxmc6/z2hghnhowlqkplip/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
) and Learn UX Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/5qu6rgzg5kc7hw0nxmc6/p8heh9h9xqn2gphq/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnV4LmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
) (which open Wednesday for new enrollments =F0=9F=8E=89) have TONS of
checklists.

=E2=80=8B
Because, when faced with a complex situation (like designing a
highly interactive app), a checklist can (a) prevent you from
making dumb mistakes and (b) act as a =E2=80=9Cbrainstorming partner=E2=80=
=9D for
best practices.

Let=E2=80=99s take a look at the =E2=80=9CStyling data=E2=80=9D checklist f=
rom the
Typography Cheatsheet in Learn UI Design. We=E2=80=99ll use a simple
task-manager as an example.

I=E2=80=99ve just dumped some labels and values onto a page. And that=E2=80=
=99s a
fine way to start =F0=9F=91=8D

=E2=80=8B

***********************
=E2=9C=85 Remove obvious labels
***********************

First item on the list. Remove obvious labels.

We can do this wherever the data is self-explanatory. I=E2=80=99m
thinking =E2=80=9CTask name=E2=80=9D and possibly even =E2=80=9CDescription=
=E2=80=9D can go.

The catch? We=E2=80=99ll have to make it clear what they are from their
styling.

=E2=80=8B
The title is bigger and bold. The descriptions is smaller and
lighter. Seems... not crazy =F0=9F=A4=B7

*******************************************************
=E2=9C=85 Combine labels and values into human-readable phrases
*******************************************************

=E2=80=9CUrgent: true=E2=80=9D is not how a human would speak. Instead, we=
=E2=80=99d say
=E2=80=9CUrgent=E2=80=9D if it=E2=80=99s urgent, and (presumably) nothing i=
f not.

Why not have the UI work that way too?

=E2=80=8B
Cool. Next!

******************************
=E2=9C=85 Display information visually
******************************

One of the best ways to fix the =E2=80=9CWALL OF TEXT=E2=80=9D feel is with
images (photos, illustrations, icons).

Here, there=E2=80=99s only one place I think that makes sense:

=E2=80=8B
Notice that since the =E2=80=9CAssigned to=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CDue=E2=80=
=9D labels/values are
all (presumably) short, I formatted them horizontally. Better use
of vertical space =F0=9F=91=8D

*********************
The finishing touches
*********************

In Learn UX Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/5qu6rgzg5kc7hw0nxmc6/z2hghnhowlqkplip/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
), one usability heuristic I repeat over and over is show what=E2=80=99s
actionable. That means figure out what the user needs to see to
make a decision as easily as possible.

In this case, the date.

=E2=80=9C1/11/22=E2=80=9D requires me to remember the current date and then
compare it to this one. But what if we did the subtraction for
our user?

And a 3-dot =E2=80=9Cactions=E2=80=9D menu icon for editing, etc.
And that wraps it up!

That=E2=80=99s not the whole checklist, but it gives you a sense of its
usefulness. Start with a bunch of label/value pairs, end with
more readable, better-looking design.

This sort of methodical, left-brain approach to design is one of
the things that students love about Learn UI Design and Learn UX
Design.

=E2=80=8B

